      "question": "Find the ratio in which the $y$-axis divides the line segment joining the points $A(5, -6)$ and $B(-1, -4)$. Also, find the point of intersection.",
      "answer": "Ratio $5:1$, Point $(0, -13/3)$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Assume the ratio is $k:1$. The coordinates of the point on the $y$-axis will be $(0, y)$.",
          "Use the section formula for the $x$-coordinate to find $k$.",
          "Substitute $k$ into the section formula for the $y$-coordinate to find the point."
        ],
        "derivation": "$0 = \\frac{k(-1) + 1(5)}{k+1} \\Rightarrow -k + 5 = 0 \\Rightarrow k = 5 \\\\ \\text{Ratio is } 5:1 \\\\ y = \\frac{5(-4) + 1(-6)}{5+1} = \\frac{-20 - 6}{6} = \\frac{-26}{6} = -\\frac{13}{3} \\\\ \\text{Point is } (0, -\\frac{13}{3})$"
      },
